        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to obtain ALMA band 7 observations of CO(3-2) and 13CO(3-2) in NGC 4696. We shall use the C34-3 configuration giving us a spatial resolution of 0.4 arc-seconds matching our HST and Chandra imaging. The primary beam is well matched to our object and we do not require ACA observations. We will use only one pointing.

The line-of-sight velocity field in NGC 4696 is of order 500 kmps, we shall therefore use the 821 kmps bandwidth for our CO (3-2) baseband. We do not require aditional continuum bands for our observations. Additionally we will put a baseband an NH3 emission line, an indicator of dense gas. All base bands are FDM mode and dual polarisation. We propose to use the standard calibration.

Scaling our sub-arcsecond HST H alpha imaging to the same flux as the [C II] herschel emission and assuming a [C II]/CO (1-0) ratio 4808 as has been found in other central group and cluster galaxies we simulate the CO emission. CO (3-2)/CO(1-0) ratios typically vary between 0.3-1.3. From the particle heating model of the filaments we expect the CO (3-2) emission to be comparable to the CO (1-0) emission. Binning our scaled HST image to our requested 0.40'' spatial bin the peak average surface brightness on the extended filaments is expected to be 2.5mJy. We expect the emission in the brighter filaments and the nucleus to be about 3 to 5 times larger.

We shall use spectral averaging to decrease the data rate.

We request a 0.73 mJY rms in a 10 kmps velocity bin, which can be achieved with 1 hour on source. This will result in the highest spectral resolution observations of such a system and the combination of the spatial and spectral resolution will allow us to measure, for the fist time, the micro-turbulent line broadening. Previous observations have been limited by the macro-turbulence of many confused filament threads.

The ALMA OT calculates the total observing time will all overheads to be 2.6 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
