    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe NGC 4696, the brightest cluster galaxy (BCG) in the Centaurus cluster with ALMA Band 7. Our primary aim is to map and measure the velocity structure of the CO (3-2) rotational emission line at sub-arcsecond resolution in the multi-phase yet quiescent filaments which surround this galaxy. The filaments in NGC 4696 cradle giant radio lobes produced by the central AGN and are the only such filaments in which dense dusty cores are apparent along their full extent, yet, like many low redshift brightest cluster galaxies, these filaments are not producing stars. The high spatial resolution of ALMA, allowing us to map the molecular gas on the same spatial scale as the new and existing HST and Chandra data, will help us answer the questions of how radio mode AGN feedback in the local universe is able to move large amounts of cool and cold gas yet, in most cases, does not efficiently promote star formation and grow these galaxies. </prp:abstract>
